data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 (.NET 10), new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `array.Reverse()` (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). The fix pattern is identical — use `.AsEnumerable()` or call `Enumerable.Reverse(array)` explicitly.
